Proper Documentation of Experiments (Dataset and Results Configuration)
1. Dataset Description
The experiment uses publicly available retinal fundus image datasets for diabetic retinopathy hemorrhage detection.
DIARETDB1 Dataset

Public dataset widely used for diabetic retinopathy research.
Contains 89 retinal fundus images.
45 images contain hemorrhages or diabetic retinopathy lesions.
Images captured using fundus cameras with a 50° field of view.
Used primarily for training the hemorrhage detection model.

DIARETDB0 Dataset
Contains 130 retinal fundus images.
110 images contain diabetic retinopathy signs.
Used as an independent testing dataset to evaluate model generalization.

Dataset Split
Dataset Split	Percentage
Training	64%
Validation	16%
Testing	20%

The dataset is divided into training, validation, and testing sets to ensure reliable evaluation and avoid overfitting.

2. Experimental Environment
Hardware Configuration
Processor: Intel Core i5 (2.4 GHz)
RAM: 16 GB
GPU: 6 GB GPu

Software Environment

The implementation was performed using Python and the following libraries:
TensorFlow / Keras
OpenCV
Scikit-learn
Scikit-image
NumPy
Matplotlib
Seaborn
These libraries were used for image preprocessing, deep learning training, and evaluation of model performance.

3. Image Preprocessing

Preprocessing improves the visibility of retinal structures and lesions.

Steps Involved

Contrast Enhancement
Applied CLAHE (Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization).
Adaptive Gamma Correction
Adjusts brightness based on gradient information.
Unsharp Masking
Enhances edges and lesion boundaries.
Green Channel Extraction
The green channel of fundus images provides better contrast for detecting retinal lesions.
These preprocessing steps help improve the detection of hemorrhages and reduce illumination variations.

4. Candidate Region Detection

Potential hemorrhage locations are identified using seed point extraction techniques.
Detection Process
Gaussian Matched Filter
Enhances dark objects such as hemorrhages.
Otsu Thresholding
Separates foreground objects from the background.
Morphological Operations
Removes noise and small artifacts.
Connected Component Analysis
Extracts candidate lesion regions.
The centroids of these detected regions are used as seed points for hemorrhage detection.

5. Image Segmentation

Segmentation is performed using Smart Window Adaptive Thresholding (SWAT).

SWAT Segmentation Steps
Extract windows around seed points.
Apply adaptive thresholding within the window.
Perform morphological filtering.
Retain the most significant connected components.
This method allows detection of hemorrhages with different sizes and intensity variations.

6. Patch Extraction

After segmentation, image patches are extracted to train the deep learning model.

Each patch contains three channels:

Green channel (RGB)
Value channel (HSV color space)
Luminance channel (CIE Lab color space)
These channels provide complementary information for detecting retinal lesions.

Patch Labels
Label	Meaning
1	Hemorrhage
0	Non-Hemorrhage

Balanced samples from both classes are used for training.

7. Deep Learning Models Used

The proposed model is compared with several well-known deep learning architectures.

Proposed Model
HemNet (Hemorrhage Detection Network)

Comparison Models
LeNet-5
AlexNet
ResNet50
VGG-16
Simple CNN
BiraNet
EfficientNetB0
InceptionV3
HemNet is a shallow convolutional neural network designed to detect hemorrhages efficiently while reducing training time.

8. Training Configuration

The following training parameters were used:

Parameter	Value
Optimizer	Adam
Learning Rate	0.001
Batch Size	16
Epochs	20
Loss Function	Categorical Cross-Entropy
Additional techniques used:
Early stopping
Learning rate reduction
Model checkpointing
These techniques help improve training stability and prevent overfitting.
9. Evaluation Metrics

Model performance was evaluated using standard medical classification metrics.

Accuracy
Accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
Sensitivity (Recall)
Sensitivity = TP / (TP + FN)
Specificity
Specificity = TN / (TN + FP)
Precision
Precision = TP / (TP + FP)

Where:

TP = True Positive
TN = True Negative
FP = False Positive
FN = False Negative
Confusion matrices were also used to visualize classification performance.
10. Result Configuration
After training, the models were evaluated using the test dataset.

The results include:
Confusion matrix analysis
Accuracy scores
Precision and recall values
ROC curves
Precision–Recall curves
The comparison shows that HemNet achieves competitive performance with significantly reduced training time compared to deeper models.
11. Key Observations

Image preprocessing significantly improves lesion detection accuracy.
Seed point extraction reduces unnecessary search regions and speeds up detection.
HemNet achieves competitive accuracy with fewer layers.
Increasing network depth does not always improve performance but increases computational cost.
